Returning to #BrexitDay  it is a sad day for me today. I have consistently said that I am proud Brit and a committed European. I refuse to let Brexit change this perspective.

We're special in our ways, but just as Denmark is special in theirs  or France  or Ireland ... name your country. Trying to quantify specialness is madness, leads to historical whimsy at best and sometimes dangerous myth making and what on earth is the point for going forwards?

Trying to defined British culture as somehow different from European is bonkers and self defeating because we're simply part of Europe (not the political European Union, but the physical, cultural and historical Europe).

Furthermore, "European" is not some dirty, enemy word. It is a grouping of countries in this patch of the world with shared history and culture. Just as Switzerland is European so is the UK (neither being part of the EU).
But divisive groups of who's "fault" it is when the going gets tough is not going to change the landscape. We're going to have to leave that behind.

I will get particularly annoyed if anyone says that Brexit didn't work because not enough people got behind or not. Please don't make that argument - if there is any sub-group of people to shoulder responsibility it's those who voted Leave and the politicians who argued it.
We will have to jointly own the consequences of this as a country. Personally, I think its going to be tougher than you think, but not catastrophic.

For my "Leaver" friends, family (its been tough) and audience. I accept the decision (see above) - I am not re-prosecuting it - future conversations will be easier if you don't go backwards and see the democratic processes as validation of intellectual arguments :)

I am not a politician, I am a scientist with a pan-European role and that pan-European scientific viewpoint is good for the UK; Like many things there is *not* a zero-sum game, and science is an area where the synergy, serendipity and just joy of working together is necessary
At this point, I am not going to waste my energy on re-prosecuting the last 3 years. As a UK citizen I am going to play my part in making the UK better place, arguing for sensible structures.

I don't think leaving is a good idea; I campaigned against in the original referendum; but I do accept in particular in the last phase with an explicit election that by the democratic processes the UK has, in particular a vote in Parliament, that we should leave, as we are today.

Now, for my "Remainer" friends, family and audience here. I have accepted the reality that we are leaving the EU. It's unlikely (though not unfeasible) that we will rejoin. It is extremely unlikely this decade.

I can't apologise enough for the actions of my country here. Deep, deep apologies again to all the non-British Europeans who have stuck at this. I - and I know many others - appreciate you as colleagues, citizens and friends.

It has also changed the tenor of the country; what is discussed on radio and by politicians gets reflected on the street, pubs and in schools. It is not... nice, nor British in my view. It is something I hope (but can't promise) Brexit happening will remove.

From these colleagues I know just how crap being a non-Brit European in the UK; the rhetoric has been nasty, the explicit hostile environment policy of the home office is ugly and so disrespectful to people who live in the UK legally, appropriately and giving so much to the UK.

I am also lucky that I work with such a diverse group of people @emblebi and across @embl - we hire scientists from anywhere across the world, but unsurprisingly have a large number of Europeans from across the broad European countries, here including UK, CH, IL :)

Which could start me on a whole ‚Äústudent debt in the US is crazy‚Äù rant - but I‚Äôll stop here.

But beyond maternity leave - I might argue that another / maybe bigger issue is that child care is far too expensive in the US for many people. This forces many families to be 1 income (or 1.5) which has a very negative and far reaching economic impact or end up borrowing to live

So - back on the original topic of maternity leave: Should we have more time paid off. Yes. 8-12 weeks paid would be a minimum i think // for both parents. It really vastly improves the relationship you build with your child - but I only have 2 datapoints to back that up üòÅ

B/ child care in the US is insanely expensive. We hunted for infant care for years - and ended up settling for unlicensed ‚Äúhighly recommended‚Äù caretaker who had 5 other kids. It was still $900/month in 2006. My older son we put in a real day care - it was $1000+/month easy.

A/ grad students make üí© money and so do many postdocs. So both spouses have to work. I think I made $19k/year when i my 1st son was born. So - double that becuase my wife and I were in the same lab
even with longer maternity leave policies we would have still have had to work these split shifts for many years - mainly because
It‚Äôs easy to remember the good parts of it all - but there we probably just as many hard days (as all parents know)
I miss the mid day lunches my wife and I had in grad school most days - while #1 was napping. I also miss the long days I had 1/1 time with my sons when they were small -
To - we worked split shifts, for 2 years for each kid. 6am-2pm and 2pm-10pm. Two cars made it possible getting the boys around and trading cars mid day every day
From - We wanted to do good science and learn the craft - but weren‚Äôt willing to work 80h a week for a nature paper or join an ultra high pressure lab
I‚Äôve been asked before - ‚ÄúHow the hell did you do that?‚Äù And my responses are usually a mix of things ranging from -
We had both our kids while we were still training (1st while we were both in grad school, 2nd while we were both doing our postdocs).

Remember that not getting a position does not mean you are not qualified or not talented. There is some luck. The job should be a good fit for both you and the person you are working with. Don't give up if you aren't successful. #academicchatter #sciencetwitter 9/9

8. Specify expected graduation. It can help determine eligibility.9. Fill out ALL fields. Specify supervisor/project/research interest.'NA' may  mean you are not downloaded from database. Many will only download applicants applying to their lab/research area.

5. For computational positions, specify what languages you are proficient in.6. Look for typos and try to create good flow in your CV.7. Don't send incessant emails. One follow up if needed is sufficient.  7/n

For example, I would stay away from saying how high your previous salary was or that your parents, grandparents or friends are scientists or doctors, so you know things. These are not relevant and may not come off well when someone is reading those details. 6/n

If you were a server, discuss your time management skills,that you can work under pressure. Were you a cashier? demonstrate how you had attention to detail (did your til balanced), etc.4. While showing why you are a good candidate is important, don't give irrelevant details. 5/n

Battle-test every assumption on your data. U can get these models to behave and reveal super interesting insights. But these are rarely plug and play. 8/8
Moral of the story: don't believe everything u read especially with powerful/ highly flexible models 7/
We've tried more complicated solutions (based on published ML literature). Nothing has so far beaten the hack above. If anyone knows of other tricks, spill the beans 6/

Simple hack to get around this issue with heterogeneous tasks. Train a naive multi task model -> fine tune for each task independently initializing from the multitask model. Will more than often improve performance per task 5/
If tasks are more homogeneous (eg. multiple chromatin markers with strong global correlation or combining TFs), naive multi tasking can help a lot 4/

Eg. of heterogeneous tasks : predict binding from sequence for many TFs (each TF is a task) with very different binding patterns, or chromatin accessibility across cell types (each cell type is a task) across a vast diversity of cell types 3/
Naive multitask training = optimizing average/sum of loss across all tasks with architecture = multiple output heads (for multiple tasks) following a shared body 2/

Here's another dirty little secret about typical NNs used in regulatory genomics/variant scoring. 'Naive' multi-task training of CNNs especially on highly heterogeneous tasks (that don't strongly reinforce each other) almost always results in suboptimal models for all tasks 1/ https://t.co/LXpuqnRDmF

As the calculation of HDX increasingly gets closer to capturing the actual exchange process (but w.o. the "chemistry") we are getting closer to seeing those rarer states. This paper is, I think, a very nice step along that path! 10/10

At the moment, however, my reading of this kind of work is that it mostly provides insight into the (dynamic) ground states rather than higher-energy exchange competent states. But this is very difficult to know because we still don't understand the actual exchange processes. 9/

Thus, eventually we may be able to use these kinds of approaches to study the actual dynamics that leads to HDX, thus making it possible to integrate MD and HDX to study transient higher-energy states. 8/

With long-timescale MD (plus MSMs, fancier analysis etc), we may now be entering an age where we can sample the fastest of the slow dynamic processes that lead to exchange. See e.g. the paper from @voelzlab and refs therein. 7/
Restraining ensembles by such models will thus, probably, model ground states but not necessarily directly the dynamics that actually leads to exchange. 6/

Most forward models are variations on older work from @e_paci @mvendruscolo14 and @rob_best_ which used structures/short MD to parameterize models for Pf of slowly exchanging amides. In effect, the resulting forward model predicts Pf from the ground state (ensemble). 5/

For structural modelling, this gives a bit of a conundrum. Do we (i) aim to find a forward model to predict the protection factor from the ground state, or (ii) do we model the actual state through which exchange occurs? Both are hard problems. 4/

We typically use the #Linderstr√∏mLang model to interpret HDX as occurring via a transient "exchange competent" state. In the EX2 regime the exptl data can be used to estimate the free energy difference between that state and the "ground state", i.e. the (log) protection factor 3/

In general, computational methods such as the BICePs approach used derive structures or ensembles to be consistent with a set of experimental data. Here, consistent means that when the data are calculated from the structure(s) using a forward model, they agree with experiment. 2/

What we really want to know is what happens to R0 now intervention has been put in place, and importantly what is the R0 going to be in other countries where the virus has been exported to. Likely these will all be significantly lower. So please take these with a grain of salt.

This means that the R0 values that are currently estimated are specific to (a) Wuhan, and (b) (mostly) pre-intervention. The R0 is going to be different for different countries/regions and will change over time.

I'll elaborate more on this later, but for now, please ignore these types of panicked statements. The reproductive number (R0) of a virus is *highly* context and time dependent and *will* change. E.g., SARS was ~3 in the beginning, but <1 after intervention. https://t.co/F1v69cVhfz

Carrying on saying "pity X is going badly, it would be so much better in the EU" will just look petty & is too easily spun as "sore losers". Instead, we need to bring the focus *on the ideas* and *why they're good*. Collaboration, freedom, internationalism, supporting immigration

Obviously, we need to keep communicating *why* things are even worse now, and how they could be different. But the messaging is critical, because the last thing we should do now is to push abstract pro-EU points most people can't relate to.

The only way forward now, I think, is for us to focus on the *substance*. On the things we can fight for *effectively* at a smaller scale, including locally. Start making a real difference in people's lives where we can.

We lost on the big ideals front, big time. What the rightwing won, hands down, was "engaging" with people. You may not like it, but they "listened" (never mind that they answered with false promises). "Remain" seems to have never really done that.

That‚Äôs just a taste - loads more harrowing details.
Remarkably, no human crew members lost (all the sled dogs were sacrificed). One invalided by severe frostbite. How they all didn‚Äôt die of exposure is beyond comprehension.
Shackleton commissions boats to go after 22 others - only on fourth attempt can he get thru pack ice

So Shackleton and two others hike 20+ miles over uncharted glaciers &mountains, with many detours. A modern attempt with modern gear found it rough going; Shackleton had worn out & rotting gear & adze as ersatz ice axe. Stumble into camp to be greeted with ‚ÄúWho the hell are you?‚Äù
Rarely does sun break thru clouds for a fix, and then only briefly as ship pitches wildly. Somehow they find island and miss reefs to find tiny harbor - but in wrong side of island

Shackleton & 5 others sail tiny (~7m) boat into some of most dangerous & stormy waters of planet aiming for distant tiny islands with whaling station; any significant error in navigation and they miss it. Gigantic waves often threaten  capsizing or swamping, as does ice buildup.
Winds rarely cooperate, but somehow they land.First landfall is great - until they realize entire beach is below high water mark. Find a second, slightly higher beach.

They can‚Äôt get off an ice floe & seem about to be swept into open sea; their flow has been ground down to less than a soccer pitch - at opportune moment a path clears and they make for a distant desolate island

If you tried the story as a movie treatment, everyone would say it was too preposterous. The men have primitive gear and are essentially never dry or warm from when they abandon ship to their rescue many months later. Weather never in their favor except at key moments

Finished reading Endurance today, classic account of Ernest Shackleton‚Äôs failed 1914 attempt to perform first crossing of Antarctica. Their ship, the book title, was trapped and then crushed by ice pack

I've been impressed by the amount of acknowledgement and support #MentalHealth in academia has gained over the past several years (and continuing), and would like to see the same for substance abuse. This topic continuing to be taboo is a big part of the problem.

I feel addiction is something we struggle to appropriately address and resolve in academia. For instance, there are so many events that operate around #alcohol. People are frequently placed in scenarios where functional alcoholism is even encouraged. This needs to stop.

As of recent, this has become a big priority in my life.Through my teens to now, many close people in my life have been negatively impacted by addiction. Some of whom are no longer with us in this world. All of these individuals are beyond worthy of love and being well.

After many valuable discussions and a lot of deep thought, I will be utilizing my newly developed (and still developing) automation/bot skillset to convert this account into a space for people to anonymously discuss #addiction and offer support, in #academia or otherwise. Why?

17/17 That's it! A warm thank-you to @BrianPlosky and the team of @MolecularCell for working with us through revisions, accepting the manuscript right before the holidays and publishing so soon thereafter! so happy to see this long project wrapped up

16/17 E/ Our FMRE-KO model does not directly reflect SNVs and indels found in patient tumors, and the HEK293 cells originate from non-cancer tissue (embryonic kidney) that does not represent typical cells of patient tumors where the FMRE was identified (kidney RCC and others).

15/17 D/ Limited epigenetic, RNA-seq and HiC data restrict the annotation of FMREs. For example, infrequent mutations in FMREs coupled with only partially matched RNA-seq data (~50%) made it challenging to identify mRNA/SNV associations of FMRE target genes.

14/17 C/ Variant calls at non-coding regions have technical and biological challenges and biases. To address this, we used high-confidence PCAWG consensus variant calls, filtered some high-suspect regions early, and manually reviewed variants in a subset of top FMREs.

13/17 B/ The heterogeneous pan-cancer cohort and our choice of multi-tissue regulatory elements prioritize prediction of pan-cancer candidate drivers and tissue-specific elements probably remain hidden. Even at ~1800 WGS tumors, the dataset appears underpowered.

12/17 The study has some important caveats: A/ somatic mutation rates vary across the genome and associate with chromatin state, replication, TF binding, etc., and may raise false flags of positive selection. We attempt to correct for this through a local mutation rate model.

11/17 Our study suggests that additional, unexplored non-coding mutations in cancer genomes may as drivers of cancer gene deregulation. In particular, distal regulatory may interact with gene promoters through 3D chromatin to carry out such function.

10/17 To wrap, we integrated multiple regulatory elements per gene over a long tail of less-frequent non-coding mutations and found an enrichment of known cancer genes and relevant pathways, suggesting that additional FMREs might be found in larger WGS datasets.

9/17 These data highlight this FMRE as a distal regulator of CCNB1IP1, while the additional genes and pathways are potentially downstream of this gene. We speculate about a late driver event of senescence or metastasis, but this needs more work of course.

I use sequencing to compare against because of the virtuous way the (both computational and experimental) technologies surrounding sequencing have developed. It's a testament to how well, despite differences,folks in the e.g. genomics and syn bio communities have worked together.

Couple with portable purification instruments (which are still not there yet but this could change) and you could go to the field to find new drugs, new materials, new reagents. A "nanopore" version of MS could tell you what you found and it would be instantly actionable

The molecules MS interrogates are also likely more actionable than the nucleic acids sequencing sees. Most drugs are designed or repurposed with a signaling or metabolic pathways, or protein complexes in a mind, "gene programs" or expression signatures are only proxies for these

This is to mention only a few of the issues -- but none are insurmountable. And the payoff for getting it right is huge: it is routinely used in many biotechs, pharma, academic labs. It can be used to interrogate proteins, metabolites, and small molecules alike.

MS is plagued by many evils: proprietary raw data formats (!), vendor-specific and machine-specific effects, windows only software, non-trivial instrument maintenance, lack of support for public repositories (props to Massbank and @GNPS_UCSD for their huge efforts)

Maybe these two branches will be as differentiated in their appearance as the Navy and Marines. Why should you care? These folks serve in the most technical parts of the military and perform duties we depend on daily in our civilian lives. Calling them space cadets is petty AF

When the Air Force split from the Army they had nearly identical uniforms to the Army in shades of brown. The blue we know today didn‚Äôt really appear until the 50s. So first iteration winks to the past but pattern and nametape points to a new future.

So why jungle camo and a new pattern? Every branch of the military gets to pick their pattern. This is a new branch with a sister branch that is the Air Force. They probably gave it a lot of thought and being that Gen Raymond is an AF man he prob didn‚Äôt want to veer too far

Today‚Äôs military bases its rare to see the suit type. Why wear camo when you have a desk job (or play in the band)? For esprit de Corps. No matter the rank, makes everyone feel they are ready to get dirty if need be. You‚Äôre part of the team. Cohesion.

Not the most flattering, I know... this professional uniform has a collared shirt. Kind of like a suit. An utility uniform ranges from business casual to scrubs. During my time this depended on the amount of starch people applied, but I think they stopped that nonsense since.

Let‚Äôs talk about uniforms. The military has uniforms for many occasions: formal, ceremonial, professional, utility, PT and theater specific combat. Being a band geek, my favorite are ceremonial ones. Also anything the Marines wear üòç here I am wearing a maternity uniform circa 99 https://t.co/Rqc1cicgZF

The Space Force just puts all of these entities under one roof, now reporting to Dept of the Air Force. They are land based soldiers with space based missions. They have been shuffled so many times and it was prob already in the works before this admin

These are real people in real uniforms working technical jobs for not great pay. They help us do simple every day things like use GPS based Google maps to get to our favorite restaurant. How much science and agriculture depend on GPS today? TY 50th Space Wing!

Other duties included keeping track of space junk falling down, or in the way of NASA operations. They cooperate on tracking debris so that new shiny satellites can do things like monitor earths climate, bring pictures of devastation in Australia etchttps://t.co/zI8cojmQq5

The arm patch is what space force used to be: US Space Command (both led by Gen Raymond). USSPACECOM reported to DOD. It included things like space based services that we rely on: GPS and satellite communications. It also unified space efforts between Army, Navy and Air Force

@toggl @DrTashaBarlow If done badly where times are adjusted to make existing workload fit within the 100% FTE then they are not useful. In fact they are harmful. There will always be debate on details, but listen to staff if they are nowhere near fitting in tasks in the expected times. (11/14)

@toggl @DrTashaBarlow So are workload models useful? To channel my inner Sir Humphrey Appleby, yes and no. Yes: they provide a rough guide to overall workload in a department. If done well, they can help argue for more resources. But they must be done well. (10/14)

@toggl @DrTashaBarlow My lectures and prep time in WM is 15.32%. I spent 13.95%. I did update lectures and I developed two new practicals using Jupyter notebooks. So the WM does include enough time to keep material up-to-date, but not enought to do a whole module revamp. (9/14)

@toggl @DrTashaBarlow I have 400 hours in the workload model to write proposals/do unfunded research, but I only spent 70 hours writing grants! I spent a lot of time on research (669 vs 237 hours), with that additional 432 hours unfunded.  (8/14)

@toggl @DrTashaBarlow Whilst the workload model and reality are quite close in broad scale, the details are very different. I spend longer working with dissertation students than the model (194 hours vs 135) and less time on marking (108 vs 177 hours). (7/14)

@toggl @DrTashaBarlow Average working hours per week: 37 hours, 17 minutes 21 seconds. My contracted hours are 37.5 hours (which includes paid breaks, so taking say 30-ish min break per day into account I overwork by ~2 hours per week). (6/14)
@toggl @DrTashaBarlow Time spent answering and writing emails (not in the WM): (at least) 95 hours 53 minutes 12 seconds (around 26.5 minutes per day). (5/14)

@toggl @DrTashaBarlow What did I time? Anything work-related when I actully did work. Not Twitter. Not reading the BBC or Guardian websites. Not breaks. Not lunches. I am entitled to paid breaks, so add ~2.5 hours per week to my average hours below to compare to contract (4/14).

Grad students are in this weird position where our projects are really important to us & we want them to work, but they‚Äôre also a part of our training. So if things don‚Äôt go well, don‚Äôt beat yourself up about it‚Äîyou‚Äôre learning. I‚Äôm going to try to  do the same.

So really, ‚Äútime wasted‚Äù isn‚Äôt a good way to look at it if I come out of it a better scientist. There are analyses I‚Äôve spent months on I‚Äôll never use, projects that went to nowhere, ideas that didn‚Äôt work, all of which have gone into making me into a well-rounded researcher.

I‚Äôm wrapping up a month of genomics labwork, a lot of which has been fixing errors I made last year üò´ Have been frustrated at loss of time & DNA, but everything‚Äôs been salvageable & I know a lot more abt the method & troubleshooting it than if the protocol had gone perfectly.

Grad students tend to be high performers who are hard on themselves, so I think it‚Äôs always worth noting that making mistakes is a critical part of the learning process. If you don‚Äôt make errors you don‚Äôt end up w the tools to recognize & fix them #phdchat

This has been a huge team effort, and wouldn't have been possible without the whole PopSim community. It's a great community to be a part of, and we're just getting started: come join us! https://t.co/lKWmaKWKDs

.. and help the authors of these vital resources get due credit. (Users are nagged to cite these resources by default, but there is a -q/--quiet flag to turn this off. We're not monsters.) There's even a -b/--bibtex-file option to write citations to BibTeX!

A really important feature is that stdpopsim writes out full citation information for every resource (simulation engine, mutation rate estimate, recombination map, genome build, demographic model, etc) used. This will hopefully motivate people to contribute new models etc..

The native output is a #tskit tree sequence, which stores the complete genetic history of the simulation, is very compact and efficient to process. Stdpopsim can support any simulation engine outputting tskit (#msprime now, SLiM soon, others maybe?).https://t.co/mBxgYqo4M0

There's a lot of work going on behind the scenes to make this possible. One of the reasons stdpopsim is needed so badly is that implementing demographic models is *hard*. We have a rigorous community QC method to make sure our models are accurate: https://t.co/3aksc1Rbf8

All you have to do is choose stuff from our "catalog": species, chromosome, genetic map and demographic model. Defaults are sensible if you don't care about particular details. Everything is linked back to the original citations if you want to dig deeper.https://t.co/vHtaaOussP https://t.co/DY1jBtWwTl

It really is easy. E.g., simulate 10^4 African samples under American admixture model and write to VCF:$ stdpopsim HomSap -d AmericanAdmixture_4B11 10000 -c chr20 > sim.trees; tskit vcf sim.trees -P 2 > sim.vcf

The goal of stdpopsim is to make doing the right thing *easy*. You can now simulate the most up-to-date available models of demographic history for several species without knowing anything about the coalescent, or reading a single paper. Full docs here:https://t.co/fIn07SQdyH

Three lessons I learned during my PhD was that 1) you CAN do creative science without a ton of money and 2) the ability to survive when things got really rough and 3) the notion that science must be agonizing and painful to be ‚Äúreal‚Äù is the antithesis to creativity

I spent the following 6 months completely aimless, with no sense of direction and had it not been for my co-mentor at that time, I would‚Äôve quit the program altogether. The DGS of my program took me on and I was able to finish with PhD in hand in 4.5 years.
In a matter of a week, I left behind half of my thesis work, was not allowed to include any of it in my dissertation, and effectively had to start from scratch 2.5 years into graduate work.

The most pivotal personal and professional moment of this decade, and one I rarely discuss, has to be receiving notice from the graduate school that I had to leave my PhD lab due to concerns for my well-being.

So going to toss this out here for anyone who might find it useful. Anxiety sucks, and there's no silver bullet, but here's another strategy to try if you need it.

Today's panic attack was bad, but this actually defused it really well. Not only do I feel a lot better, but I also have a game plan with clear milestones for the short-term- which can help prevent my anxiety from getting out of hand.

Everyone is different, but for me, a key strategy to stopping a panic attack is 1) recognizing what the proximate cause is, 2) distraction, and 3) making a plan with small, achievable goals.Today was a pretty masterful example of that.

We talked about Star Wars a bit, and then the analyses I'd been running. He then worked with me to outline very specifically and concretely plans to wrap up some projects over the next couple of weeks.

My advisor came in, and could immediately tell what was up. He asked me what the trigger was- didn't try to say it was unreasonable or anything, just had me identify what had set it off to pull me back to reality.

Sometimes I see people ask what to do for someone who's having a panic attack.Earlier today, if you couldn't tell from my tweets, I was having one. I was by myself in my office, checking on some programs I'd been running over break.
